//   JavaScript Arrays - PACKED vs HOLEY (V8 Engine Internals)
//   Topic: "You don't know arrays in JavaScript" - JSVU / V8-debug

// V8 (Chrome/Node's JavaScript engine) optimizes arrays internally based on their elements' type.
// The more optimized the array, the faster the performance.

// HIERARCHY (Most Optimized -> Least Optimized)
//
//   PACKED_SMI_ELEMENTS       ->  Best  (only small integers, no gaps)
//   PACKED_DOUBLE_ELEMENTS    ->        (only numbers/doubles, no gaps)
//   PACKED_ELEMENTS           ->        (any value, no gaps)
//   HOLEY_SMI_ELEMENTS        ->        (only integers, WITH gaps)
//   HOLEY_DOUBLE_ELEMENTS     ->        (only doubles, WITH gaps)
//   HOLEY_ELEMENTS            ->  Worst (any value, WITH gaps)
//
// IMPORTANT RULE: Once an array is downgraded to HOLEY, it will never be upgraded
// back to PACKED — even if all holes are filled later. V8 keeps the HOLEY stamp forever.

// EXAMPLE 1 — PACKED_SMI_ELEMENTS (Best case)

const arrOne = [1, 2, 3];
// All integers (SMI = Small Integer), no gaps.
// V8 internally: PACKED_SMI_ELEMENTS (fastest)

console.log(arrOne); // [1, 2, 3]

// EXAMPLE 2 — PACKED_SMI -> PACKED_DOUBLE (downgrade)

const arrTwo = [1, 2, 3];
// Currently: PACKED_SMI_ELEMENTS

arrTwo.push(4.5);
// 4.5 is a float/double, not an SMI.
// V8 downgrades the entire array:
// PACKED_SMI_ELEMENTS -> PACKED_DOUBLE_ELEMENTS

console.log(arrTwo); // [1, 2, 3, 4.5]

// EXAMPLE 3 — PACKED_DOUBLE -> PACKED_ELEMENTS (downgrade)

const arrThree = [1, 2, 3, 4.5];
// Currently: PACKED_DOUBLE_ELEMENTS

arrThree.push("hello");
// A string was pushed — the array is no longer exclusively numbers.
// V8: PACKED_DOUBLE_ELEMENTS -> PACKED_ELEMENTS

console.log(arrThree); // [1, 2, 3, 4.5, 'hello']

// EXAMPLE 4 — new Array(n) creates a HOLEY array immediately

const arrFour = new Array(3);
// new Array(3) means: reserve 3 EMPTY HOLES.
// No values provided yet, only size declared.
// V8 internally: HOLEY_SMI_ELEMENTS — already downgraded on creation.

arrFour[0] = "1"; // HOLEY_ELEMENTS (string assigned, holey stamp already applied)
arrFour[1] = "2"; // HOLEY_ELEMENTS
arrFour[2] = "3"; // HOLEY_ELEMENTS

// Note: the array now has no remaining holes — all slots are filled.
// However, V8 applied the HOLEY stamp at creation and it never gets removed.
// The array will NOT be upgraded back to PACKED.

console.log(arrFour); // ['1', '2', '3']
// Looks identical to a PACKED array but internally: HOLEY_ELEMENTS (slow)

// EXAMPLE 5 — [] + push stays PACKED

const arrFive = [];
// Empty array literal — V8 starts with PACKED_SMI_ELEMENTS.

arrFive.push("1"); // PACKED_ELEMENTS (string caused downgrade from SMI, but still PACKED)
arrFive.push("2"); // PACKED_ELEMENTS
arrFive.push("3"); // PACKED_ELEMENTS

// No holes were ever created, so the array remains PACKED.
// Much better performance than new Array(3). [if you added arr.push(NaN) or arr.push(undefined), it would have been HOLEY_ELEMENTS then]

console.log(arrFive); // ['1', '2', '3']
// Internally: PACKED_ELEMENTS (fast)

// EXAMPLE 6 — How holes are created

const arrSix = [1, 2, 3];
// Currently: PACKED_SMI_ELEMENTS

arrSix[10] = 99;
// Indices 3 through 9 have no assigned value — these are holes.
// V8: PACKED_SMI -> HOLEY_SMI_ELEMENTS

console.log(arrSix); // [1, 2, 3, empty x 7, 99]
console.log(arrSix[5]); // undefined (hole)
console.log(arrSix.length); // 11

// EXAMPLE 7 — delete also creates a hole

const arrSeven = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
// Currently: PACKED_SMI_ELEMENTS

delete arrSeven[2];
// Index 2 is now a hole.
// V8: HOLEY_SMI_ELEMENTS

console.log(arrSeven); // [1, 2, empty, 4, 5]
console.log(arrSeven[2]); // undefined

// To remove an element without creating a hole, use splice instead of delete:
// arrSeven.splice(2, 1) -> [1, 2, 4, 5]  stays PACKED

// REAL WORLD IMPACT — Why does this matter?

// For every element access in a HOLEY array, V8 must perform additional checks:
//   1. Is the index within the array bounds?
//   2. Is there a hole at this index?
//   3. Does the prototype chain provide a value for this index?
// These extra checks slow down iteration — especially forEach, map, filter, reduce.

// In PACKED arrays, none of these checks are needed. V8 accesses the value directly.

// BEST PRACTICES — Summary

// BAD — using new Array(n)
const bad = new Array(100); // Immediately HOLEY

// GOOD — start with [], use push
const good = [];
for (let i = 0; i < 100; i++) good.push(i); // Stays PACKED

// BAD — using delete to remove an element
const arr = [1, 2, 3];
delete arr[1]; // Creates a hole -> HOLEY

// GOOD — use splice instead
const arr2 = [1, 2, 3];
arr2.splice(1, 1); // [1, 3] -> Stays PACKED

// BAD — leaving gaps in an array literal
const sparse = [1, , , 4]; // Holes in the middle -> HOLEY

// GOOD — provide all values
const dense = [1, 2, 3, 4]; // PACKED
